Views on abortion are possibly influenced by the way different political parties view the issue, with the Conservative Party, the National Party and the Left Green Party supporting increased access to abortion and the Progressives, Social Democratic Alliance and the Pirate Party opposing abortion.13 Currently, abortion is legal and considered up to the 16th week of pregnancy under the Icelandic Pregnancy and Fetal Person’s Protection Law (“Law”).14 The general principle of the Law is that each person is initially equal upon birth by granting full person’s rights and protection to a fetus.15 The Law only allows abortions if it is recommended by two physicians and termination of pregnancy up to 20 weeks after conception can only be done using surgical or medical means that do not harm the fetus.16 Beyond 20 weeks and up to twenty-six weeks, abortions can only be conducted for health or fetal defects reasons.17 More specifically, termination of pregnancy in Iceland is regulated in the following sections and subsections of the Law:
1. Section 2 permits a woman to terminate a pregnancy only up to the 16th week of pregnancy and a fertilized egg must be placed in the nonpregnancy category.18 The two conditions of subsection 2 must be satisfied for a termination to take place at any time:
a. When the pregnant woman wants to terminate her pregnancy until the 16th week of initiation of pregnancy or at “any earlier date before the date any fetal heartbeat is detected”.19
